        <h3>Tools</h3>
        <h4>Libraries / NuGet Packages</h4>     
        using (var list = Bs.List(ListType.Unordered).Begin())
        {        
            <li>
                <strong><a href="http://attributerouting.net/">AttributeRouting</a></strong>
                <br/>Define your routes using attributes on action methods in ASP.NET MVC and Web API. Probably less relevant now that MVC 5 includes it's own attribute routing, but still valuable for legacy projects.
            </li>           
            <li>
                <strong><a href="http://automapper.org/">AutoMapper</a></strong>
                <br/>Automatic mapping between objects (I.e., domain models to view models). Also highly configurable to meet many different use cases.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong><a href="https://github.com/hazzik/DelegateDecompiler">DelegateDecompiler</a></strong>
                <br />Converts computed entity properties for use on the server. @Html.PostLink("See my blog post on the topic", x => x.computed_properties_and_entity_framework).
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong><a href="http://www.dotlesscss.org/">dotless</a></strong>
                <br/>A LESS CSS parser for C#.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong><a href="http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/data/ef.aspx">Entity Framework</a></strong>
                <br/>I've tried a number of ORMs over the years, and my favorite by far has been Entity Framework. The EF team also seems highly committed to delivering regular improvements, which is always a positive.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong><a href="http://getglimpse.com/">Glimpse</a></strong>
                <br/>Real time diagnostics & insights of web applications. I can't even count the number of debugging hours Glimpse has saved me.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong><a href="http://htmlagilitypack.codeplex.com/">HtmlAgilityPack</a></strong>
                <br/>This is an oldie but a goodie and hasn't been updated in a number of years, but it still works well and is still the best/only way to work with an HTML DOM tree in code.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong><a href="http://humanizr.net/">Humanizer</a></strong>
                <br/>Presenting information is one of the most important aspects of most applications, and this library makes it easy to manipulate and display strings, enums, dates, times, timespans, numbers and quantities.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong><a href="http://james.newtonking.com/json">Json.NET</a></strong>
                <br/>By far the best way of working with JSON in .NET.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong><a href="http://razorengine.codeplex.com/">RazorEngine</a></strong>
                <br/>I keep finding little use cases for this library that enables using Razor as a templating engine.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong><a href="http://t4mvc.codeplex.com/">T4MVC</a></strong>
                <br/>I hate magic strings, and T4MVC is so embedded into my process now I literally can't imaging writing a full MVC application without it.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong><a href="https://unity.codeplex.com/">Unity</a></strong>
                <br/>I don't always use an IoC container, but when I do, it's (usually) Unity.
            </li>    
